\begin_layout Title
Lecture I: Dynamic Programming in Continuous Time - Poisson Events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These notes begin with a review of Poisson processes, as a starting point
 to think of continuous-time stochastic events.
 Then, we derive a Bellman equation in continuous time, the HJB equation.
 The advantages of continuous time are that you can obtain, often, tractable
 solutions.
 There are also some numerical advantages.
 We will cover some numerical approaches at the end of the lecture.
 This block is useful throughout our course.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Preliminary: Poisson Processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
From Bernoulli to Poisson.

\series default
 Divide the real line into a sequence of time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\left\{ 1,2,3,...,\infty\right\} .$
\end_inset

 Assume that every periods, there is a chance of an occurrence of a given
 event.
 We let the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

 be the one that turns into a 1 when an event has occurred by time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This function is a random variable because it is a function defined in
 an underlying probability space.
 We let that probability be, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Because the process is Bernoulli, the outcome is independent of time by
 definition.
 Thus, the probability that an event has not occurred by period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ N_{t}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\right)^{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The chance that the event occurs exactly at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ N_{t+1}=1,N_{t}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\right)^{t}p.
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left\{ N_{t+s}=0,N_{t}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\right)^{t}\left(1-p\right)^{s}=\left(1-p\right)^{t+s}=\Pr\left\{ N_{t+s}=0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the probability that the event has not realized by time 
\begin_inset Formula $t+s$
\end_inset

 is the same as the probability that it did not realize up to time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ N_{t+s}=0|N_{t}=0\right\} =\frac{\Pr\left\{ N_{t+s}=0,N_{t}=0\right\} }{\Pr\left\{ N_{t}=0\right\} }=\left(1-p\right)^{s}=\Pr\left\{ N_{s}=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

This process is is stationary—it is invariant to initial conditions.
 It's chance of no events up to 
\begin_inset Formula $t+s$
\end_inset

 conditional on no event up to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the same as not observing an event in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 periods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we want to study what happens as we divided the real line into a finer
 and finer sets.
 Thus, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\left\{ \Delta,2\Delta,...\infty\right\} $
\end_inset

 and work by shrinking these into finer and finer intervals.
 However, we study the probability in this problem in a particular way.
 We cannot simply divide the real line into finer and finer points without
 adjusting the probability.
 Otherwise, as we continue doing so, we would eventually have infinite Bernoulli
 trials in a single period.
 Instead, we have to be more careful and specify a ratio for the probabilities:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda\Delta=p\left(\Delta\right).
\]

\end_inset

Thus, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\rightarrow0,$
\end_inset

 the probability shrinks, but the rate at which it does is constant.
 The date can be divided into the number of intervals via:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t=\Delta\times n\left(\Delta,t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Let's now compute the chances of seeing the event at a particular date:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left\{ N_{t}=1,N_{t-\Delta}=0\right\} =\left(1-p\left(\Delta\right)\right)^{n\left(\Delta,t\right)-\Delta}p\left(\Delta\right).
\]

\end_inset

Note that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, this defines a proability of occurrence of the event at exactly the date
 
\begin_inset Formula $t.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we write this expression as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{n\left(\Delta,t\right)-\Delta}\lambda\Delta.
\]

\end_inset

Since as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\rightarrow0,$
\end_inset

 the probability of the event becomes a density, we can define the following
 density:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(t;\lambda\right)=\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\frac{\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{n\left(\Delta,t\right)-\Delta}\lambda}{\Delta}\Delta.
\]

\end_inset

I'm skipping many steps from measure theory that prove the continuity of
 probabilities.
 For now, we can compute this object:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 &  & \lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{t/\Delta}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{-\Delta}\lambda\\
 & = & \left(\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{1/\Delta}\right)^{t}\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{-\Delta}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and by definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp$
\end_inset

, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
 & = & \left(\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{1/\Delta}\right)^{t}\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow\infty}\left(1-\lambda\Delta\right)^{-\Delta}\lambda\\
 & = & \lambda\exp\left(-\lambda t\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's integrate this density from zero to infinity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\infty}\lambda\exp\left(-\lambda t\right)dt=-\exp\left(-\lambda t\right)|_{t=0}^{\infty}=-0-\left(-1\right)=1.
\]

\end_inset

This is the density of the probability that the event occurs at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 The c.d.f.
 of the event is this:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\tau}\lambda\exp\left(-\lambda t\right)dt=-\exp\left(-\lambda t\right)|_{t=0}^{\tau}=\exp\left(-\lambda\tau\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Naturally, the density of the event not occurring by 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 can be obtained in a similar way.
 The probability that the event has not occurred up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\exp\left(-\lambda\tau\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Connection with Poisson Distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Poisson processes are understood as random 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(\omega\right)$
\end_inset

 variable taking values in 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{+}$
\end_inset

.
 These are the only processes satisfying the conditions of:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
independent increments 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
stationarity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
that expected number of arrivals in a given fraction of time is constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Poisson distribution of is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left(N=k\right)=\frac{\lambda^{k}e^{-\lambda}}{k!}
\]

\end_inset

This comes from taking the Bernoulli process above, but adding different
 intervals of size 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, and then taking the same limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A poisson counting process generalizes the result to any moment in time,
 expressing things in terms of rates, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda t$
\end_inset

.
 Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left(N_{t}=k\right)=\frac{\left(\lambda t\right)^{k}e^{-\lambda t}}{k!}
\]

\end_inset

Additional useful property of the poisson process is its additivity characterist
ic; namely for 
\begin_inset Formula $X+Y$
\end_inset

 poisson events with rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{y},$
\end_inset

 it holds that :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{t}^{1}+N_{t}^{2}\sim\text{Poisson}(\lambda_{x}+\lambda_{y})
\]

\end_inset

The stopping time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\inf\left\{ s:N_{t+s}-N_{t}=1\right\} $
\end_inset

 has and exponential density with parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

—the same as the exponential distribution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\sim\lambda\cdot\exp(-\lambda t)
\]

\end_inset

so obviously the stopping time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\min(\tau_{1},\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

 for two independent poisson processes with rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 is associated with the 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}+X_{2}$
\end_inset

 poisson random variable.
 Therefore, its distribution is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\sim\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)\cdot\exp(-\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)t)
\]

\end_inset

Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left[\tau=\tau_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

 is computed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr(\tau_{1}=t,N_{t}^{2}=0)=\Pr(\tau_{1}=t)\cdot\Pr(N_{t}^{2}=0)=\left(\lambda_{1}\cdot\exp(-\lambda_{1}t)\right)\cdot\exp\left(-\lambda_{2}t\right).
\]

\end_inset

which is the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}^{1}$
\end_inset

 jumps at t while 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}^{2}$
\end_inset

 remains at 0.
 Integrating over the whole domain yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{o}^{\infty}\left(\lambda_{1}\cdot\exp(-\lambda_{1}t)\right)\cdot\exp\left(-\lambda_{2}t\right)dt & = & \int_{o}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\lambda_{2}t\right)dt-\int_{o}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)t\right)\lambda_{1}dt\\
 & = & \frac{\lambda_{1}}{\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and to check that this is correct we look at 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left[\tau=\tau_{1}\right]+P\left[\tau=\tau_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

, by symmetry: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\lambda_{1}}{\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)}+\frac{\lambda_{2}}{\left(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}\right)}=1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Critically, the time between two Poisson events is distributed exponential:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\ge N_{t}+1|N_{t}\right]=1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right).
\]

\end_inset

We make use of this distribution repeatedly below.
 The density is, of course, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(N_{t+\Delta}\ge N_{t}+1|N_{t}\right)=1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman Equation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Net present values in continuous time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now move on to study the continuous time version of Bellman equations.
 Let's begin first computing a net present value formula, without the maximizati
on.
 We try to compute:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{t}=\sum_{s=0}^{\infty}\beta^{s}U\left(c_{t+s}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 is a known path.
 We can conduct the following convenient change of variables and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\exp\left(-\rho\right).$
\end_inset

 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\beta.$
\end_inset

 Thus, we can write the expression as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{t}=\sum_{s=0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right).
\]

\end_inset

We want to make the same computations as time intervals, become smaller
 and smaller, as we did with the Bernoulli example above.
 Naturally, we need to weight utility by the length of the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

, to make things consistent.
 Thus, the value is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t,\Delta\right)=\sum_{s=0:\Delta:\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)\Delta.
\]

\end_inset

Taking the limit yields, by definition of Lebesgue integral,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}V\left(t,\Delta\right)=\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds.
\]

\end_inset

From now on, abandon the notation that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 for the time interval and we use it to compute derivatives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we want to compute how the value changes as a function of calendar
 time.
 Thus, we compute:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right)}{\Delta}.
\]

\end_inset

Why are we interested in this object? Because it will be useful to characterize
 Continuous Time problems that often do not have solutions in discrete time.
 By definition we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right) & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds\\
 & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds\\
 & = & \int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho\left(z+\Delta\right)\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+z}\right)dz
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the last line is a change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $z=s-\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right)=\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds.
\]

\end_inset

Then, we obtain:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{V\left(t+\Delta\right)-V\left(t\right)}{\Delta}=\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\Delta}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next line just follows a number of definitions.
 Thus, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{V}=\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\cdot\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{0}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\Delta}.
\]

\end_inset

The last term can be evaluated via Leibnitz's rule.
 First term, is the product of two limits.
 Note that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)-1}{\Delta}\equiv\frac{\partial\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)}{\partial\Delta}|_{\Delta=0}=-\rho.
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds-\int_{0}^{0}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\Delta} & \equiv & \frac{\partial\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\partial\Delta}|_{\Delta=0}\\
 & = & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta}\right)|_{s=0}=U\left(c_{t}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\dot{V} & = & \rho\cdot\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds-U\left(c_{t}\right)\rightarrow\\
\rho V & = & \dot{V}+U\left(c_{t+s}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

I assumed to this point that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a constant, then 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a constant, and we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{V}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=U\left(c\right)/\rho.
\]

\end_inset

This is nothing but the famous net present value function.
 It's is the continuous-time analogue of 
\begin_inset Formula $U\left(c\right)/\left(1-\beta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This approximation is exact for 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

—although the net-present value is undefined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Exercise I.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What if 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 varies with time? Can you find the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Exercise II.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Derive the corresponding formula when the discount factor is time varying.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
When Consumption is a function of a State Variable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume now that 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a function of some variable 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and a function of time as well, rather than a function of time only.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}=c\left(S_{t},t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a known function of time, above.
 In particular, we assume that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{S}_{t}=\mu\left(S_{t}\right)S_{t}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, we define the value function as 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(S,t\right)$
\end_inset

 and do the same calculations as we did above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t+\Delta\right)-V\left(S_{t},t\right)}{\Delta} & = & \lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+\Delta+s}\right)ds\\
 & \ldots & -\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds}{\Delta}\\
 & = & \lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\cdot\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(S_{t+\Delta+s}\right)\right)ds\\
 & \ldots & -\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(S_{s}\right)\right)ds}{\Delta}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The term on the right-hand side remains identical.
 The term on the left is slightly different:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t+\Delta\right)-V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t\right)+V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t\right)-V\left(S,t\right)}{\Delta} & = & \lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t+\Delta\right)-V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t\right)}{\Delta}\\
 & \ldots & +\lim_{\Delta\rightarrow0}\frac{V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t\right)-V\left(S,t\right)}{\Delta}\\
 & = & \frac{\partial V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t+\Delta\right)}{\partial\Delta}|_{\Delta=0}+\frac{\partial V\left(S_{t+\Delta},t\right)}{\partial\Delta}|_{\Delta=0}\\
 & = & \dot{V}+V_{s}\dot{S}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we obtain the following formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V=U\left(c\left(S\right)\right)+V_{s}\dot{S}+\dot{V}.
\]

\end_inset

When consumption is only a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is no longer a function of time—we need the time formula because it become
 redundant.
 Thus, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V=U\left(c\left(S\right)\right)+V_{s}\mu\left(S\right)S.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example I.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(S\right)=\bar{c}\cdot S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(s\right)=\left(r-\bar{c}\right)\cdot S$
\end_inset

.
 How do you interpret this terms? Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a power utility: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(C\right)=\frac{C^{1-\sigma}-1}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Show that the value function is of the form: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are undetermined coefficients.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is by ``Guess and Verify'' where we match coefficients: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that under the conjecture: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V=\frac{\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}S^{1-\sigma}}{1-\sigma}+AS^{1-\sigma}\left(r-\bar{c}\right)-\frac{1}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Grouping terms: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V=\frac{\left(\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}+\left(1-\sigma\right)\left(r-\bar{c}\right)A\right)}{1-\sigma}S^{1-\sigma}-\frac{1}{1-\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

What if 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 varies with time? Can you find the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

? Thus, matching coefficients, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho A=\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}+\left(1-\sigma\right)\left(r-\bar{c}\right)A\rightarrow A=\frac{\bar{c}^{1-\sigma}}{\rho-\left(1-\sigma\right)\left(r-\bar{c}\right)}.
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=1/\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
When Consumption is Maximized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What if consumption is actually maximized.
 Since the HJB equation is valid for any path of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

, optimal consumption will maximize: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\max_{c}U\left(c\right)+V_{s}\mu\left(S,c\right)S+\dot{V}
\]

\end_inset

if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(S,c\right)$
\end_inset

 is a control variable.
 This is true because the problem does not depend on past decisions—the
 principle of optimality.
 Hence, the reference to Richard Bellman.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Example II.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(s\right)=r\cdot S-c$
\end_inset

 but let 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 be now maximized.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a power utility: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(C\right)=\frac{C^{1-\sigma}-1}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma},
\]

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(\frac{\rho-\left(1-\sigma\right)r}{\sigma}\right)^{-\sigma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=1/\rho$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The proof is again by ``Guess and Verify
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 where I match coefficients: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V(S)=\frac{AS^{1-\sigma}-B}{1-\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that under the conjecture: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U'\left(c\right)=V_{s}=AS^{-\sigma}\rightarrow c=\left(AS^{-\sigma}\right)^{-1/\sigma}=A^{-1/\sigma}S.
\]

\end_inset

This implies that the solution to the previous example is identical, but
 now must solve a fixed point.
 Namely, it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}=A^{-1/\sigma}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Thus, this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}=A/\left(1-\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 in the previous example.
 Thus: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho\frac{A}{1-\sigma}=\frac{A^{1-1/\sigma}}{1-\sigma}+rA-A^{1-1/\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

Simplifying terms by dividing both sides by 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\rho}{1-\sigma}=\frac{\sigma}{1-\sigma}A^{-1/\sigma}+r,
\]

\end_inset

and from here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A^{-1/\sigma}=\frac{\rho-\left(1-\sigma\right)r}{\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

The proof for 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the same as above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can connect this term with the Euler Equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{c}=A^{-1/\sigma}\dot{S}=A^{-1/\sigma}\left(r-\bar{c}\right)S=A^{-1/\sigma}\frac{\sigma r-\rho+\left(1-\sigma\right)r}{\sigma}S=A^{-1/\sigma}\frac{r-\rho}{\sigma}S
\]

\end_inset

The Euler equation will be derived from first principles later, but here
 note that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\dot{c}}{c}=\frac{r-\rho}{\sigma}S.
\]

\end_inset

We will encounter this Euler equation in multiple places.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
HJB equation with Poisson Events
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Two Consecutive Events Cannot Happen.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A first observation regards the possibility of two subsequent events.
 Recall that the probability that the first Poisson event is exponential.
 By independence, we can show:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq1|N_{t}=0\right]=1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)
\]

\end_inset

and likewise, the probability that two events happen is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq2|N_{t}=0\right]=\int_{0}^{\Delta}\lambda\exp\left(-\lambda\tau\right)\cdot\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\left(\Delta-\tau\right)\right)\right)d\tau.
\]

\end_inset

Then, consider: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq1\right]}{\Delta}=\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)}{\Delta}=\lambda.
\]

\end_inset

But now for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq2|N_{t}=0\right]$
\end_inset

, notice that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\Pr\left[N_{t+\Delta}\geq2|N_{t}=0\right]}{\Delta}=\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\int_{0}^{\Delta}\lambda\exp\left(-\lambda\tau\right)\cdot\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\left(\Delta-\tau\right)\right)\right)}{\Delta}d\tau=0.
\]

\end_inset

This can be verified since the term inside cannot blow up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Consecutive Jumps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now move on to Hamilton-Jacobi-Bellman equation, but allowing Jumps.
 We compute:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\left(t,X_{t}\right)=\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c_{t+s}\right)ds|X_{t}\right].
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t+s}$
\end_inset

 is a Poisson process.
 What do we mean by this? It's a process that switches value upon the realizatio
n of a Poisson event.
 We can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $|X_{t}$
\end_inset

 as the conditioning over a state given by the value before the switch.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}\in\left\{ L,H\right\} $
\end_inset

 implies that there are only two states.
 For simplicity, here I assume it takes high and low values, thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=C\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}=H,$
\end_inset

 for simplicity.
 The expectation refers to the current state.
 We compute the value as before, regarding a short time interval.
 We split the integral between two terms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=H\right]|,X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=L\right]|,X_{0}=H\right].
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Consider the probability of only one switch, ignoring the probabilities
 of more than one switch by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{\Delta}^{\infty}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{t+\Delta}=L\right]+O\left(\Delta\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Then, exploiting the Markovian structure: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\Delta\right)V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)\\
 & + & \exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)V\left(t+\Delta,L\right)+O\left(\Delta\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We perform the same operation as before, subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)$
\end_inset

 from both sides.
 We obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\left(t,H\right)-V\left(t+\Delta,H\right) & = & \mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t+s}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]\\
 & + & \left(\exp\left(-\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\Delta\right)-1\right)V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)+\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)V\left(t+\Delta,L\right)+O\left(\Delta\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and taking limits, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{V\left(t,H\right)-V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)}{\Delta} & = & \lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\mathbb{E}\left[\int_{0}^{\Delta}\exp\left(-\rho s\right)U\left(c\left(X_{t}\right)\right)ds|X_{0}=H\right]}{\Delta}\\
 & + & \lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\left(\exp\left(-\left(\rho+\lambda\right)\Delta\right)-1\right)}{\Delta}\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}V\left(t+\Delta,H\right)\\
 & + & \lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\exp\left(-\rho\Delta\right)\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{\left(1-\exp\left(-\lambda\Delta\right)\right)}{\Delta}\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}V\left(t+\Delta,L\right)+\lim_{\Delta\downarrow0}\frac{O\left(\Delta\right)}{\Delta}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

From the same arguments used above, we arrive at: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(t,H\right)=U\left(c\left(H\right)\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(t,L\right)-V\left(t,H\right)\right]+\dot{V},
\]

\end_inset

and by analogy: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho V\left(t,L\right)=U\left(c\left(L\right)\right)+\lambda\left[V\left(t,H\right)-V\left(t,L\right)\right]+\dot{V}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

